SIMPLE: file
RECORDS: 6

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: File
<hw>File</hw> <pr>(f⟦imac⟧l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>file</ets> row (cf. Pr., Sp., Pg., & It. <ets>fila</ets>), LL.
<ets>fila</ets>, fr. L. <ets>filum</ets> a thread. Cf.
<er>Enfilade</er>, <er>Filament</er>, <er>Fillet</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>An orderly succession; a line; a row</def>; as:
<sd>(a)</sd> <sd>(Mil.)</sd> <def>A row of soldiers ranged one behind
another; -- in contradistinction to <contr>rank</contr>, which
designates a row of soldiers standing abreast; a number consisting the
depth of a body of troops, which, in the ordinary modern formation,
consists of two men, the battalion standing two deep, or in two
ranks.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The number of <xex>files</xex> in a company describes
its width, as the number of ranks does its depth; thus, 100 men in
⟦ldquo⟧fours deep⟦rdquo⟧ would be spoken of as 25 <xex>files</xex> in 4
ranks. <rj><au>Farrow.</au></rj> </note></p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>An orderly collection of papers, arranged in
sequence or classified for preservation and reference; as,
<xex>files</xex> of letters or of newspapers; this mail brings English
<xex>files</xex> to the 15th instant.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>The line,
wire, or other contrivance, by which papers are put and kept in
order.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is upon a <qex>file</qex> with the duke's other letters.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj></p>

<p><sd>(d)</sd> <def>A roll or list.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧A <xex>file</xex> of
all the gentry.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj></p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Course of thought; thread of narration.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let me resume the <qex>file</qex> of my narration.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir H. Wotton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(computers)</fld> <def>a collection of data on a
digital recording medium treated as a unit for the purpose of recording,
reading, storage, or indexing; -- such a <ex>file</ex> is typically
accessible by computer programs by the use of a file name. The data may
be of any type codable digitally, such as simple ASCII-coded text,
complex binary-coded data, or an executable program, or may be itself a
collection of other files.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>File firing</b></col>, <cd>the act of firing by file, or
each file independently of others.</cd> -- <col><b>File
leader</b></col>, <cd>the soldier at the front of any file, who covers
and leads those in rear of him.</cd> -- <col><b>File marching</b></col>,
<cd>the marching of a line two deep, when faced to the right or left, so
that the front and rear rank march side by side.</cd> <au>Brande &
C.</au> --<mcol><col><b>Indian file</b></col>, <it>or</it>
<col><b>Single file</b></col></mcol>, <cd>a line of people marching one
behind another; a single row. Also used adverbially; as, to march
<ex>Indian file</ex>.</cd> -- <col><b>On file</b></col>, <cd>preserved
in an orderly collection; recorded in some database.</cd> --
<col><b>Rank and file</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>The body of soldiers
constituting the mass of an army, including corporals and privates.</cd>
<au>Wilhelm.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>Those who constitute the bulk or
working members of a party, society, etc., in distinction from the
leaders.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>File</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: File
<hw>File</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Filed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Filing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To set in order; to
arrange, or lay away, esp. as papers in a methodical manner for
preservation and reverence; to place on file; to insert in its proper
place in an arranged body of papers.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I would have my several courses and my dishes well
<qex>filed</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Beau. & Fl.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To bring before a court or legislative body by
presenting proper papers in a regular way; <as>as, to <ex>file</ex> a
petition or bill</as>.</def> <rj><au>Burrill.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>To put upon the files or among the
records of a court; to note on (a paper) the fact date of its reception
in court.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>file</qex> a paper, on the part of a party, is to place it
in the official custody of the clerk. To <qex>file</qex>, on the part of
the clerk, is to indorse upon the paper the date of its reception, and
retain it in his office, subject to inspection by whomsoever it may
concern.</q> <rj><qau>Burrill.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>File</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: File
<hw>File</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>filer</ets>.]</ety>
<fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>To march in a file or line, as soldiers, not
abreast, but one after another; -- generally with
<xex>off</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To file with</b></col>, <cd>to follow closely, as one
soldier after another in file; to keep pace.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My endeavors⟦br⟧
Have ever come too short of my desires,⟦br⟧
Yet <qex>filed with</qex> my abilities.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>File</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: File
<hw>File</hw> <pr>(f⟦imac⟧l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>fe⟦oacute⟧l</ets>; akin to D. <ets>viji</ets>, OHG.
<ets>f⟦imac⟧la</ets>, <ets>f⟦imac⟧hala</ets>, G. <ets>feile</ets>, Sw.
<ets>fil</ets>, Dan. <ets>fiil</ets>, cf. Icel.
<ets>⟦thorn⟧⟦emac⟧l</ets>, Russ. <ets>pila</ets>, and Skr.
<ets>pi⟦cced⟧</ets> to cut out, adorn; perh. akin to E.
<ets>paint</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A steel instrument, having
cutting ridges or teeth, made by indentation with a chisel, used for
abrading or smoothing other substances, as metals, wood, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ A <xex>file</xex> differs from a <xex>rasp</xex> in
having the furrows made by straight cuts of a chisel, either single or
crossed, while the rasp has coarse, single teeth, raised by the
pyramidal end of a triangular punch.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Anything employed to smooth, polish, or rasp,
literally or figuratively.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Mock the nice touches of the critic's <qex>file</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Akenside.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A shrewd or artful person.</def>
<mark>[Slang]</mark> <rj><au>Fielding.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Will is an old <qex>file</qex> in spite of his smooth face.</q>
<rj><qau>Thackeray.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Bastard file</b></col>, <col><b>Cross
file</b></col></mcol>, <cd>etc. See under <er>Bastard</er>,
<er>Cross</er>, etc.</cd> -- <col><b>Cross-cut file</b></col>, <cd>a
file having two sets of teeth crossing obliquely.</cd> -- <col><b>File
blank</b></col>, <cd>a steel blank shaped and ground ready for cutting
to form a file.</cd> -- <col><b>File cutter</b></col>, <cd>a maker of
files.</cd> -- <col><b>Second-cut file</b></col>, <cd>a file having
teeth of a grade next finer than bastard.</cd> -- <col><b>Single-cut
file</b></col>, <cd>a file having only one set of parallel teeth; a
float.</cd> -- <col><b>Smooth file</b></col>, <cd>a file having teeth so
fine as to make an almost smooth surface.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>File</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: File
<hw>File</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To rub, smooth, or cut
away, with a file; to sharpen with a file; <as>as, to <ex>file</ex> a
saw or a tooth</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To smooth or polish as with a file.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>File</qex> your tongue to a little more courtesy.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>File</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: File
<hw>File</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>fulen</ets>,
<ets>filen</ets>, <ets>foulen</ets>, AS. <ets>f<?/lan</ets>, fr. f<?/l
foul. See <er>Foul</er>, and cf. <er>Defile</er>, <pos>v.
t.</pos>]</ety> <def>To make foul; to defile.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All his hairy breast with blood was <qex>filed</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For Banquo's issue have I <qex>filed</qex> my mind.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>File closer</ent>⟦br⟧
